[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In mathematical optimization theory, **duality** or the **duality principle** is the principle that optimization problems may be viewed from either of two perspectives, the **primal problem** or the **dual problem**.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] If the primal is a minimization problem then the dual is a maximization problem (and vice versa).
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Any feasible solution to the primal (minimization) problem is at least as large as any feasible solution to the dual (maximization) problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Therefore, the solution to the primal is an upper bound to the solution of the dual, and the solution of the dual is a lower bound to the solution of the primal.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In general, the optimal values of the primal and dual problems need not be equal.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Their difference is called the duality gap.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] For convex optimization problems, the duality gap is zero under a constraint qualification condition.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Usually the term "dual problem" refers to the *Lagrangian dual problem* but other dual problems are used – for example, the Wolfe dual problem and the Fenchel dual problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The Lagrangian dual problem is obtained by forming the Lagrangian of a minimization problem by using nonnegative Lagrange multipliers to add the constraints to the objective function, and then solving for the primal variable values that minimize the original objective function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The latter condition is trivially, but not always conveniently, satisfied for the characteristic function (i.e. $I_{\mathrm {constraints} }(x)=0$ for x satisfying the constraints and $I_{\mathrm {constraints} }(x)=\infty$ otherwise).
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Then extend ${\tilde {f}}$ to a perturbation function $F:X\times Y\to \mathbb {R} \cup \{+\infty \}$ such that $F(x,0)={\tilde {f}}(x)$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] where $F^{*}$ is the convex conjugate in both variables and $\sup$ denotes the supremum (least upper bound).
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The duality gap is the difference between the values of any primal solutions and any dual solutions.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] If $d^{*}$ is the optimal dual value and $p^{*}$ is the optimal primal value, then the duality gap is equal to $p^{*}-d^{*}$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] This value is always greater than or equal to 0 (for minimization problems).
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The duality gap is zero if and only if strong duality holds.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Otherwise the gap is strictly positive and weak duality holds.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In computational optimization, another "duality gap" is often reported, which is the difference in value between any dual solution and the value of a feasible but suboptimal iterate for the primal problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Linear programming problems are optimization problems in which the objective function and the constraints are all linear.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In the primal problem, the objective function is a linear combination of *n* variables.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] There are *m* constraints, each of which places an upper bound on a linear combination of the *n* variables.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The goal is to maximize the value of the objective function subject to the constraints.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] A *solution* is a vector (a list) of *n* values that achieves the maximum value for the objective function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In the dual problem, the objective function is a linear combination of the *m* values that are the limits in the *m* constraints from the primal problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] There are *n* dual constraints, each of which places a lower bound on a linear combination of *m* dual variables.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In the linear case, in the primal problem, from each sub-optimal point that satisfies all the constraints, there is a direction or subspace of directions to move that increases the objective function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Moving in any such direction is said to remove slack between the candidate solution and one or more constraints.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] An *infeasible* value of the candidate solution is one that exceeds one or more of the constraints.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In the dual problem, the dual vector multiplies the constraints that determine the positions of the constraints in the primal.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Varying the dual vector in the dual problem is equivalent to revising the upper bounds in the primal problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] That is, the dual vector is minimized in order to remove slack between the candidate positions of the constraints and the actual optimum.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] An infeasible value of the dual vector is one that is too low.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] It sets the candidate positions of one or more of the constraints in a position that excludes the actual optimum.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] This intuition is made formal by the equations in Linear programming: Duality.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In nonlinear programming, the constraints are not necessarily linear.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Nonetheless, many of the same principles apply.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] To ensure that the global maximum of a non-linear problem can be identified easily, the problem formulation often requires that the functions be convex and have compact lower level sets.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] This is the significance of the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] They provide necessary conditions for identifying local optima of non-linear programming problems.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] There are additional conditions (constraint qualifications) that are necessary so that it will be possible to define the direction to an *optimal* solution.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] An optimal solution is one that is a local optimum, but possibly not a global optimum.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The problem has constraints; we would like to convert it to a program without constraints.
