[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The optimal solution to the dual program is a lower bound for the optimal solution of the original (primal) program; this is the *weak duality* principle.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] If the primal problem is convex and bounded from below, and there exists a point in which all nonlinear constraints are strictly satisfied (Slater's condition), then the optimal solution to the dual program *equals* the optimal solution of the primal program; this is the *strong duality* principle.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Note that, to use either the weak or the strong duality principle, we need a way to compute $g(\lambda )$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] In general this may be hard, as we need to solve a different minimization problem for every $\lambda$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] But for some classes of functions, it is possible to get an explicit formula for $g(\lambda )$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Solving the primal and dual programs together is often easier than solving only one of them.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] Examples are linear programming and quadratic programming.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] A better and more general approach to duality is provided by Fenchel's duality theorem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The vectors $\lambda$ and $\nu$ are called the *dual variables* or *Lagrange multiplier vectors* associated with the problem.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The dual function g is concave, even when the initial problem is not convex, because it is a point-wise infimum of affine functions.
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] The dual function yields lower bounds on the optimal value $p^{*}$ of the initial problem; for any $\lambda \geq 0$ and any $\nu$ we have $g(\lambda ,\nu )\leq p^{*}$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/duality-optimization] If a constraint qualification such as Slater's condition holds and the original problem is convex, then we have strong duality, i.e. $d^{*}=\max _{\lambda \geq 0,\nu }g(\lambda ,\nu )=\inf f_{0}=p^{*}$ .
