[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In mathematical optimization, the **ellipsoid method** is an iterative method for minimizing convex functions over convex sets.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method generates a sequence of ellipsoids whose volume uniformly decreases at every step, thus enclosing a minimizer of a convex function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] When specialized to solving feasible linear optimization problems with rational data, the ellipsoid method is an algorithm which finds an optimal solution in a number of steps that is polynomial in the input size.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method has a long history.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] As an iterative method, a preliminary version was introduced by Naum Z.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In 1972, an approximation algorithm for real convex minimization was studied by Arkadi Nemirovski and David B.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] As an algorithm for solving linear programming problems with rational data, the ellipsoid algorithm was studied by Leonid Khachiyan; Khachiyan's achievement was to prove the polynomial-time solvability of linear programs.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] As such, having an algorithm that is *guaranteed* to be polynomial for all cases was a theoretical breakthrough.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Khachiyan's work showed, for the first time, that there can be algorithms for solving linear programs whose runtime can be proven to be polynomial.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In practice, however, the algorithm is fairly slow and of little practical interest, though it provided inspiration for later work that turned out to be of much greater practical use.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Specifically, Karmarkar's algorithm, an interior-point method, is much faster than the ellipsoid method in practice.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Karmarkar's algorithm is also faster in the worst case.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoidal algorithm allows complexity theorists to achieve (worst-case) bounds that depend on the dimension of the problem and on the size of the data, but not on the number of rows, so it remained important in combinatorial optimization theory for many years.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Only in the 21st century have interior-point algorithms with similar complexity properties appeared.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] A convex minimization problem consists of the following ingredients.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Inequality-constrained minimization of a function that is zero everywhere corresponds to the problem of simply identifying any feasible point.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] It turns out that any linear programming problem can be reduced to a linear feasibility problem (i.e. minimize the zero function subject to some linear inequality and equality constraints).
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] One way to do this is by combining the primal and dual linear programs together into one program, and adding the additional (linear) constraint that the value of the primal solution is no worse than the value of the dual solution.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] Another way is to treat the objective of the linear program as an additional constraint, and use binary search to find the optimum value.
