[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method has several variants, depending on what cuts exactly are used in each step.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In the **central-cut ellipsoid method**, the cuts are always through the center of the current ellipsoid.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The input is a rational number *ε*>0, a convex body *K* given by a **weak separation oracle**, and a number *R* such that S(0,*R*) (the ball of radius R around the origin) contains *K*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The number of steps is $N:=\lceil 5n\log(1/\epsilon )+5n^{2}\log(2R)\rceil$ , the number of required accuracy digits is *p* := 8*N*, and the required accuracy of the separation oracle is *d* := 2−*p*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In the **deep-cut ellipsoid method**, the cuts remove more than half of the ellipsoid in each step.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] This makes it faster to discover that *K* is empty.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] However, when *K* is nonempty, there are examples in which the central-cut method finds a feasible point faster.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The use of deep cuts does not change the order of magnitude of the run-time.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] In the **shallow-cut ellipsoid method**, the cuts remove less than half of the ellipsoid in each step.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] This variant is not very useful in practice, but it has theoretical importance: it allows to prove results that cannot be derived from other variants.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The input is a rational number *ε*>0, a convex body *K* given by a **shallow separation oracle**, and a number *R* such that S(0,*R*) contains *K*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/ellipsoid-method] The relative efficiency of the methods depends on the time required for finding a separating hyperplane, which depends on the application: if the runtime is $O(n^{t})$ for $t\leq 2.5$ then the circumscribed method is more efficient, but if $t>2.5$ then the inscribed method is more efficient.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] In contrast to active-set methods (such as the simplex method) which traverses the *boundary* of the feasible region, and the ellipsoid method which bounds the feasible region from *outside*, an IPM reaches a best solution by traversing the *interior* of the feasible region—hence the name.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] An interior point method was discovered by Soviet mathematician I.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The method was reinvented in the U.S. in the mid-1980s.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] In 1984, Narendra Karmarkar developed a method for linear programming called Karmarkar's algorithm, which runs in polynomial time ( $O(n^{3.5}L)$ operations on *L*-bit numbers, where *n* is the number of variables and constants), and is also very efficient in practice.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Karmarkar's paper created a surge of interest in interior point methods.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Two years later, James Renegar invented the first *path-following* interior-point method, with run-time $O(n^{3}L)$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The method was later extended from linear to convex optimization problems, based on a self-concordant barrier function used to encode the convex set.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Any convex optimization problem can be transformed into minimizing (or maximizing) a linear function over a convex set by converting to the epigraph form.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The idea of encoding the feasible set using a barrier and designing barrier methods was studied by Anthony V.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] McCormick, and others in the early 1960s.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] These ideas were mainly developed for general nonlinear programming, but they were later abandoned due to the presence of more competitive methods for this class of problems (e.g. sequential quadratic programming).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Yurii Nesterov and Arkadi Nemirovski came up with a special class of such barriers that can be used to encode any convex set.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] They guarantee that the number of iterations of the algorithm is bounded by a polynomial in the dimension and accuracy of the solution.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The class of primal-dual path-following interior-point methods is considered the most successful.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Mehrotra's predictor–corrector algorithm provides the basis for most implementations of this class of methods.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] We are given a convex program of the form: ${\begin{aligned}{\underset {x\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}}{\text{minimize}}}\quad &f(x)\\{\text{subject to}}\quad &x\in G.\end{aligned}}$ where f is a convex function and G is a convex set.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Without loss of generality, we can assume that the objective *f* is a linear function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The dimension of this coefficient vector is called the *size* of the program.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] A *numerical solver* for a given family of programs is an algorithm that, given the coefficient vector, generates a sequence of approximate solutions *xt* for *t*=1,2,..., using finitely many arithmetic operations.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] where *V* is some data-dependent constant, e.g., the difference between the largest and smallest value in the feasible set.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] In other words, *V*/*ε* is the "relative accuracy" of the solution - the accuracy w.r.t. the largest coefficient. log(*V*/*ε*) represents the number of "accuracy digits".
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Therefore, a solver is 'polynomial' if each additional digit of accuracy requires a number of operations that is polynomial in the problem size.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Given a convex optimization program (P) with constraints, we can convert it to an *unconstrained* program by adding a barrier function.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Specifically, let *b* be a smooth convex function, defined in the interior of the feasible region *G*, such that for any sequence $\{x_{j}\in {\textbf {G}}\}$ whose limit is on the boundary of *G*: $\lim _{j\to \infty }b(x_{j})=\infty$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] We also assume that *b* is non-degenerate, that is: $b''(x)$ is positive definite for all x in interior(G).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Technically the program is restricted, since *b* is defined only in the interior of *G*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] But practically, it is possible to solve it as an unconstrained program, since any solver trying to minimize the function will not approach the boundary, where *b* approaches infinity.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Therefore, (*Pt*) has a unique solution - denote it by *x**(*t*).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The function *x** is a continuous function of *t*, which is called the *central path*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] All limit points of *x**, as *t* approaches infinity, are optimal solutions of the original program (P).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The main challenge in proving that the method is polytime is that, as the penalty parameter grows, the solution gets near the boundary, and the function becomes steeper.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The run-time of solvers such as Newton's method becomes longer, and it is hard to prove that the total runtime is polynomial.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] They proved that, in this case, the difference *xi* - *x**(*ti*) remains at most 0.01, and f(*xi*) - f* is at most ${\frac {2m}{t_{j}}}$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Thus, the solution accuracy is proportional to ${\frac {1}{t_{j}}}$ , so to add a single accuracy-digit, it is sufficient to multiply *ti* by 2 (or any other constant factor), which requires $O({\sqrt {m}})$ Newton steps.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Since each Newton step takes O(*m n*2) operations, the total complexity is O(*m3/2 n*2) operations for accuracy digit.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Yuri Nesterov extended the idea from linear to non-linear programs.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] He noted that the main property of the logarithmic barrier, used in the above proofs, is that it is self-concordant with a finite barrier parameter.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Therefore, many other classes of convex programs can be solved in polytime using a path-following method, if we can find a suitable self-concordant barrier function for their feasible region.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] We can also assume that *G* is bounded (we can easily make it bounded by adding a constraint |*x*|≤*R* for some sufficiently large *R*).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] To use the interior-point method, we need a self-concordant barrier for *G*.
