[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] To initialize the path-following methods, we need a point in the relative interior of the feasible region *G*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] In other words: if *G* is defined by the inequalities *gi*(*x*) ≤ 0, then we need some *x* for which *gi*(*x*) < 0 for all *i* in 1,...,*m*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] If we do not have such a point, we need to find one using a so-called **phase I method**.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] A simple phase-I method is to solve the following convex program: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{minimize}}\quad &s\\{\text{subject to}}\quad &g_{i}(x)\leq s{\text{ for }}i=1,\dots ,m\end{aligned}}$ Denote the optimal solution by x*,*s**.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] For this program it is easy to get an interior point: we can take arbitrarily *x*=0, and take *s* to be any number larger than max(*f*1(0),...,*fm*(0)).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] Therefore, it can be solved using interior-point methods.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] However, the run-time is proportional to log(1/*s**).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] As s* comes near 0, it becomes harder and harder to find an exact solution to the phase-I problem, and thus harder to decide whether the original problem is feasible.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The theoretic guarantees assume that the penalty parameter is increased at the rate $\mu =\left(1+r/{\sqrt {M}}\right)$ , so the worst-case number of required Newton steps is $O({\sqrt {M}})$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] 2 or more), then the worst-case number of required Newton steps is in $O(M)$ .
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] However, in practice, larger *μ* leads to a much faster convergence.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] These methods are called *long-step methods*.
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] In practice, if *μ* is between 3 and 100, then the program converges within 20-40 Newton steps, regardless of the number of constraints (though the runtime of each Newton step of course grows with the number of constraints).
[src:simplex-algorithm/interior-point-method] The exact value of *μ* within this range has little effect on the performance.
